To implement a global sorting feature, we will use the exact same strategy we just used for the `isAdding` state.

Because `Navbar` and `Taskboard` are siblings, they cannot talk to each other directly. We must **lift the sorting state up** to `App.tsx` (their parent):

1. **`App.tsx`** will hold the state of the current sorting direction (`'asc'` or `'desc'`).
2. **`Navbar.tsx`** will display the dropdown. When a user selects a different option, it calls a function in `App.tsx` to update the state.
3. **`App.tsx`** passes the sorting value down to **`Taskboard.tsx`**.
4. **`Taskboard.tsx`** uses this value on the fly to sort the tasks before they are drawn on screen.

Let's implement this! It only takes a few minor updates.

---

### 1. Update `types.ts`

Let's add a quick custom type for our sorting directions so TypeScript can keep us safe.

```typescript
// types.ts
export type Category = 'Todo' | 'In Progress' | 'Done';
export type SortDirection = 'asc' | 'desc'; // 👈 New type

export interface Subtask {
  id: string;
  title: string;
}

export interface TaskItem {
  id: string;
  title: string;
  category: Category;
  subtask: Subtask[];
  dueDate?: string; 
}

```

